    <h2 class="article__title"><a href="/blog/upgrading-to-jekyll-4/">Upgrading to Jekyll 4</a></h2>
  
  
  <section class="article__meta">
    
      <ul class="article__tags">
        
          
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
              <li class="article__tag"><a href="/blog/tags/jekyll/" class="article__tag__link bg--red">Jekyll</a></li>
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
        
          
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
              <li class="article__tag"><a href="/blog/tags/github/" class="article__tag__link bg--dark-gray">GitHub</a></li>
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
        
      </ul>
    
    
    <time class="article__date" datetime="2020-04-15T10:41:00-04:00">Apr 15, 2020</time>
    
  </section>
  
  <section class="article__content">
    

    

    
      <p>Jekyll 4.0 is out in the world, and brings upon many improvements over 3.x.</p>

<p>Notably, your site should build <em>much</em> faster now thanks to super-powered caching and content transformations. You can see a <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/news/2019/08/20/jekyll-4-0-0-released/">full list of changes here</a>.</p>

<p>While GitHub Pages is still pinned to <a href="https://pages.github.com/versions/">Jekyll 3.8.x</a>, it‚Äôs possible to start using Jekyll 4 today with a little help from Siteleaf.</p>

<p>Check out our upgrade guide to get started: <br />
<strong><a href="https://learn.siteleaf.com/themes/upgrading-from-jekyll-3-to-4/">Upgrading from Jekyll 3.x to 4.x</a></strong> ‚Üí</p>

<p>Here‚Äôs to speedy rendering! üçÉ</p>

    
    
  </section>
</article>


  

<article class="article">
  
    <h2 class="article__title"><a href="/blog/remote-themes/">Introducing remote themes</a></h2>
  
  
  <section class="article__meta">
    
      <ul class="article__tags">
        
          
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
              <li class="article__tag"><a href="/blog/tags/jekyll/" class="article__tag__link bg--red">Jekyll</a></li>
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
        
          
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
              <li class="article__tag"><a href="/blog/tags/github/" class="article__tag__link bg--dark-gray">GitHub</a></li>
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
            
            
          
        
      </ul>
    
    
    <time class="article__date" datetime="2017-11-30T13:00:00-05:00">Nov 30, 2017</time>
    
  </section>
  
  <section class="article__content">
    

    

    
      <p>Some exciting news! GitHub Pages <a href="https://github.com/blog/2464-use-any-theme-with-github-pages">has announced</a> support for loading remote themes from any GitHub-hosted repository. This is also supported on Siteleaf as of today, whether you publish to GitHub or anywhere else.</p>

<p>Remote themes are similar to <a href="https://learn.siteleaf.com/themes/gem-based-themes/">Gem-based themes</a>, but do not require <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Gemfile</code> changes or whitelisting. This means you can now use any of the hundreds of community-curated themes available on GitHub.com, or create your own without having to publish a Gem.</p>

<p>Jekyll themes package layouts, includes, and stylesheets in a way that can be overridden by your site‚Äôs content. It‚Äôs a great way to maintain a separation of content and code, and makes it possible to share themes across multiple sites.</p>

    
    
      <a href="/blog/remote-themes/" class="article__content__more">Read more</a>
    
  </section>
</article>


  

